  "text": "In a planar channel with a thickness ( − ) under its surface, the fluctuations Δ due to these emission-capture fluxes of electrons at the surface (see Figure 1 (a)) will lead to fluctuations Δ in the conductance measured between the two terminals of the channel. These fluctuations Δ and those emanating from fluctuations in the conductivity of its material, provided its thickness is constant, would be indistinguishable. Thus, assuming naively that is constant, we will find in the conductance of the channel of the 2TD the trapping effects due to this planar trap, which will mislead us towards a deep \"bulk trap\" with thermal energy = eV because emission-capture processes over an SBB are thermally activated with = eV [CITATION_1] . This feature allowed us to measure SBBs by photoconductance frequency resolved spectroscopy [CITATION_2] , which previously was considered photoconductivity frequency resolved spectroscopy (PCFRS). This planar trap in the surface leads us to consider that the data of [CITATION_3] are excellent PC data that we will use to determine the PC gain of these photoconductors operating as photo-FETs under low illumination (e.g., not conductivity data).",
